6/ Finally - make sure to use common sense. DYOR. Double check. If it’s too good to be true, it probably is. Don’t ever sign anything without doing your research. Verify from independent trusted sources. All of these things will help you avoid scams.
5/ Always take a second to do extra Due Diligence and DYOR. An extra step of safety with double checking or verifying something can save you from your wallet being drained.

4/ Turn off your DMs on Discord. Discord is one of the easiest ways for scammers to get you. Make sure you turn off your DMs. Any reputable project or brand will never DM you first. So if someone DMs you first on Discord without having had a conversation prior. Be weary!
3/ Double check with people you trust if a link is safe. This is key. Have a close circle of people you trust in the space and if you are unsure about something just ask and get feedback.

Just this past week we have seen about 100 new founders of @moonbirds_xyz offering free mints. These scams happen because people think these are the real founders and are legitimate (they buy verified accounts and change the name).

2/ If it’s too good to be true, then it probably is. This applies to all of the above. Scammers will prey on vulnerabilities with promises of quick cash. Stay on guard and question everything (yes it’s pessimistic but we need to push scammers out of this space).
Always double check links and never click on anything that looks suspicious. Plus, make sure you are getting links from the official Twitter or Discord of an account, not one that someone sent you.

1/ Make sure you always always double check any links you are sent. Scammers will send links with one letter changed from the original. If you don’t double check you could think that you are clicking on a legitimate link.

5.1/ Hacking influencers accounts and posing as them solves this problem for scammers so the end consumer needs to be wary. These can be very difficult to spot.
5/ Impersonation scams - This has happened many times with high profile celebrities and influencers being impersonated. Part of the difficulty of running a scam is social proof.

4.1/ This type of scam can include using false links and sending people to fake web pages that are there to capture your information or get access to you wallet which can result in it being drained. Always double check links, even if from someone reputable.
4/ Phishing scams - These can get the most experience users in the space so something to watch out for. Phishing scams have been around for a long time prior to crypto but are still used a lot.

3.1/ By the time you enter the fake giveaway it’s too late and you have been scammed. These can be difficult to spot as they may be impersonating someone or can spread quickly as people re-share on social platforms - falsely adding to social proof.

3/ Giveaway scams - You’ve probably seen this happen on Twitter or Discord where a scammer will pretend to be running a giveaway for a coin/token or NFT project. You will either have to connect your wallet or send some money to enter.
2.1/ Any reputable brand ❌WILL NEVER DM YOU ❌asking you to invest. Never send money to strangers on the internet.
2/ Investment scams - Another prominent type of scam, these can be found on Instagram, TG or DC. Scammers will message you with investment opportunities and will ask for money.
1.1/ The majority of the underlying scams will take place on these platforms. Tech support scams can be one of the most prominent types of scams on these platforms.

1/ Telegram and Discord scams - TG and DC can be a breeding ground for scammers unfortunately. They are used as community managers and builders but are also a place for lots of new faces to fall prey to scammers.
